How does new work?
Creates empty object
Sets prototype link
Binds this to object
Returns object

We can manually implement it:
                              function myNew(Constructor, ...args) {
                                  // Step 1
                                  let obj = {};
                              
                                  // Step 2
                                  obj.__proto__ = Constructor.prototype;
                              
                                  // Step 3
                                  let result = Constructor.apply(obj, args);
                              
                                  // Step 4
                                  return (typeof result === "object" && result !== null) ? result : obj;
                              }

                                function Person(name) {
                                    this.name = name;
                                }
                                
                                const p1 = myNew(Person, "Sam");
                             
                                console.log(p1.name); // Sam
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
How Prototype Chain Lookup Works
When you access:      p1.sayHello();
JS does NOT immediately look inside p1.
It follows this algorithm:

Step-by-step lookup:
Look inside p1 itself.
If not found → look inside p1.__proto__
If not found → look inside its prototype’s prototype
Continue until null
If still not found → undefined

Example:
                      function Person(name) {
                          this.name = name;
                      }
                      
                      Person.prototype.sayHello = function() {
                          console.log("Hello");
                      };
                      
                      const p1 = new Person("Sam");
                      
                      p1.sayHello();

Lookup path:
                        p1
                          ↓
                        Person.prototype
                          ↓
                        Object.prototype
                          ↓
                        null
                        That chain is called Prototype Chain
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

How instanceof Works Internally
When you write:   p1 instanceof Person

JS checks: Is Person.prototype somewhere in p1’s prototype chain?
Internally it’s roughly like:
                              function myInstanceof(obj, Constructor) {
                                  let proto = obj.__proto__;
                              
                                  while (proto !== null) {
                                      if (proto === Constructor.prototype) {
                                          return true;
                                      }
                                      proto = proto.__proto__;
                                  }
                              
                                  return false;
                              }
So:       p1 instanceof Person  // true
Because:  p1.__proto__ === Person.prototype
