JS inheritance is a little different from classical languages like Java or C++, because JS uses prototypal inheritance.

Modern Way (ES6 Class Syntax). Much cleaner.
                                class Person {
                                    constructor(name) {
                                        this.name = name;
                                    }
                                
                                    sayHello() {
                                        console.log("Hello " + this.name);
                                    }
                                }
Child class:
                                  class Student extends Person {
                                      constructor(name, grade) {
                                          super(name);  // calls parent constructor
                                          this.grade = grade;
                                      }
                                  
                                      study() {
                                          console.log(this.name + " is studying");
                                      }
                                  }

const s1 = new Student("Sam", "A");
s1.sayHello();  // inherited
s1.study();     // own method

What Does extends Do?
Behind the scenes:
Student.prototype.__proto__ = Person.prototype;
So it creates the same prototype chain as manual version.

What Does super() Do?
Inside child constructor:
super(name);
It calls the parent constructor.
If you don’t call super() before using this, JS throws error.
