Method Overriding
Overriding means: Child class provides its own version of a parent method.
👇 Example
                          class Person {
                              greet() {
                                  console.log("Hello from Person");
                              }
                          }
                          
                          class Student extends Person {
                              greet() {
                                  console.log("Hello from Student");
                              }
                          }
const s1 = new Student();
s1.greet(); // Hello from Student
Because JS finds greet() in Student.prototype first and stops there.That’s overriding.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using super in Methods
Sometimes you want: Use parent logic + add extra behavior.
Example:
                                            class Person {
                                                greet() {
                                                    console.log("Hello");
                                                }
                                            }
                                            
                                            class Student extends Person {
                                                greet() {
                                                    super.greet();  // call parent version
                                                    console.log("I am a student");
                                                }
                                            }

Output:
Hello
I am a student

🔹 Important
super.method() works only inside class methods.
Behind the scenes it basically calls:        Person.prototype.greet.call(this);
