Multiple Inheritance in JS?
Short answer: ❌ JavaScript does NOT support multiple inheritance.
You cannot do:
class A {}
class B {}
class C extends A, B {}  // ❌ Not allowed

But… you can simulate it using:
✅ Mixins
Example:
                        const canStudy = {
                            study() {
                                console.log("Studying...");
                            }
                        };
                        
                        const canPlay = {
                            play() {
                                console.log("Playing...");
                            }
                        };

                        class Student {}
                        Object.assign(Student.prototype, canStudy, canPlay);
                        
                        const s1 = new Student();
                        s1.study();
                        s1.play();

This copies methods into the prototype.
That’s how JS handles “multiple behavior”.
